{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17514545","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17514545"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:23:29+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:23:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12328"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12328","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12328"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.25,0.18,0.17,0.09,0.31]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4848"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78079"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4848","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4848"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12328"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63501"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"602"},{"type":"tags","id":"2560"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"6192"},{"type":"tags","id":"7173"},{"type":"tags","id":"9222"},{"type":"tags","id":"11234"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7827"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7950"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26733"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42737"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43317"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78079","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78079"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 55-year-old woman presents to her general practitioner with a one month history of pain in the back of her right arm, forearm and back of her right hand. The pain started after she had a fall in her bathroom. The pain has increased progressively and is burning and is aggravated by the movement of her neck. She also is unable to extend her arm at the elbow joint. On examination her triceps reflex is found diminished, all the other reflexes are normal, and she also has a sensory deficit in one area of her upper limb.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely area of sensory deficit in this scenario?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Lateral deltoid","Palmar thumb and index finger","Palmar surface of the little finger","Axilla","Middle finger"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient will have a sensory deficit in the \u003Cstrong\u003Emiddle finger\u003C/strong\u003E because she is presenting with cervical radiculopathy affecting cervical nerve root C7. The history of trauma which can be a cause of cervical radiculopathy by several methods. She also has pain in the posterior arm, dorsal forearm and dorsal hand, all three of them are affected by C7 radiculopathy. The middle finger and dorsal forearm are the area of the upper limb supplied by the C7 nerve root. Motor deficits involve weakness of movements that are controlled by the triceps muscle.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Elateral deltoid\u003C/strong\u003E is supplied by the C5 nerve root which is characterized by loss of bicep reflex, a sensory deficit in the lateral deltoid, motor deficit of the rhomboid, infraspinatus, deltoid and pain in the lateral arm and scapular region.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESensory supply of the \u003Cstrong\u003Epalmar aspect of thumb and index finger \u003C/strong\u003Eis by cervical nerve root C6 which is associated with a diminished bicep reflex, sensory deficit in the palmar aspect of thumb and index finger, motor Impairment of biceps and pronator teres and pain in the lateral forearm, thumb and index finger.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003EPalmar surface of the little finger\u0027s \u003C/strong\u003Esensory supply is by cervical nerve root C8, cervical radiculopathy at this level will cause a diminished reflex of finger flexors, sensory deficit in the palmar surface of the little finger, medial hand, and forearm, motor deficit involving abductor pollis brevis, abductor digiti minimi, first dorsal interosseous and pain in the fourth, fifth fingers, medial hand and forearm.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe sensory supply of the \u003Cstrong\u003Eaxilla\u003C/strong\u003E is by the nerve root of T1 and the radiculopathy at this level will result in a diminished reflex of finger flexors, sensory deficit in the axilla, medial arm, anteromedial forearm, the motor deficit will be the same as C8 (abductor pollis brevis, abductor digiti minimi, first dorsal interosseous), pain in the medial arm and axillary region.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The middle finger and dorsal forearm are supplied by cervical nerve root C7.","C7 radiculopathy can present with pain in the posterior arm, dorsal forearm, and dorsal hand, along with motor deficits such as weakness in arm extension."],"references":["Waxenbaum JA, Reddy V, Bordoni B. Anatomy, Head and Neck: Cervical Nerves. 2023 Jul 24. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30844163. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30844163/","Hong CG, Nam WD. Reliability and Diagnostic Accuracy of Standard Dermatomes and Myotomes for Determining the Pathologic Level in Surgically Verified Patients With Cervical Radiculopathy. Neurospine. 2022 Dec;19(4):1006-1012. doi: 10.14245/ns.2244194.097. Epub 2022 Dec 31. PMID: 36597659; PMCID: PMC9816603. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC9816603/","Kang KC, Lee HS, Lee JH. Cervical Radiculopathy Focus on Characteristics and Differential Diagnosis. Asian Spine J. 2020 Dec;14(6):921-930. doi: 10.31616/asj.2020.0647. Epub 2020 Dec 22. PMID: 33373515; PMCID: PMC7788378. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC7788378/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63501"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12328"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63501","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63501"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-09T12:59:04+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-09T13:00:28+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4848"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78079"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"34","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/34"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Orthopaedics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","lin